rces, the latest example of the growing interconnectedness of Musk=E2=80=99=
s =0Acompanies.=0A=0AUnder a proposed arrangement as described to investors=
, Tesla would license =0AxAI=E2=80=99s artificial-intelligence models to he=
lp power its driver-assistance =0Asoftware, called Full Self-Driving, and s=
hare some of that revenue with the =0Astartup, according to people familiar=
 with the matter. xAI would assist in =0Adeveloping other features for Tesl=
a, including a Siri-like voice assistant =0Ainside its electric cars and so=
ftware to power its humanoid robot Optimus, the =0Apeople said.=0A=0AThe te=
rms of any revenue-sharing agreement between xAI and Tesla would depend =0A=
in part upon how extensively Tesla relied on xAI=E2=80=99s technology as op=
posed to its =0Aown, the people said. xAI executives have discussed an even=
 revenue split from =0ATesla=E2=80=99s FSD, one of the people said.=0A=0AWh=
at=3F (=E2=80=9CWSJ is talking nonsense,=E2=80=9D Musk replied =0A<https://=
x.com/elonmusk/status/1832619430762705190> on X.) It is worth saying =0Atha=
t xAI wasfounded in March 2023 <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XAI_(company)=
>=0A, while Musk has been saying that Tesla would roll out fully self-drivi=
ng cars =0Awithin a year or twostarting in about 2015 =0A<https://jalopnik.=
com/elon-musk-tesla-self-driving-cars-anniversary-autopilot-1850432357/slid=
es/5>=0A. It=E2=80=99s a little weird that half of Tesla=E2=80=99s self-dri=
ving revenue would be =0Aattributable to xAI=E2=80=99s technology=3F Also w=
here exactly did xAI get this =0Atechnology=3F I mean=3F=0A=0AxAI has hired=
 employees from Tesla, including several who have worked directly =0Aon the=
 Autopilot team focused on developing self-driving capabilities. Musk =0Aal=
so diverted thousands of hard-to-get Nvidia GPUs from Tesla to xAI last yea=
r. =0AAfter that move became public, Musk said that =E2=80=9CTesla had no p=
lace to send the =0ANvidia chips to turn them on, so they would have just s=
at in a warehouse.=E2=80=9D=0A=0AJust new frontiers in corporate governance=
 here:=0A=0A * Start a company, take it public and sell tens of billions of=
 dollars of =0Ashares while remaining CEO. =0A * Start a new startup. =0A *=
 As CEO of the public company, tell your employees to help the startup buil=
d =0Aits product. =0A * Have the startup license the product back to the pu=
blic company.=0AYou have to admire it. Why would he even do this=3F I do no=
t think that it is to =0Amake more money for himself, though I suppose that=
's possible. The best =0Aexplanation that I have heard is alignment of ince=
ntives: Instead of a single=0AElon Musk Conglomerate =0A<https://www.bloomb=
erg.com/opinion/articles/2024-08-12/leverage-goes-down-when-markets-go-down=
=3Fcmpid=3DBBD090924_MONEYSTUFF&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_source=3Dnewsletter&=
utm_term=3D240909&utm_campaign=3Dmoneystuff>=0A that pursues all of Musk=E2=
=80=99s Mars-oriented whims, he needs lots of different =0Acompanies to pur=
sue each whim, so that the employees of each company are fully =0Amotivated=
 =E2=80=94 by the company=E2=80=99s clear mission and by stock-based compen=
sation =E2=80=94 to =0Aachieve that company=E2=80=99s goals. When artificia=
l intelligence became a plausible =0Abusiness, it arguably made sense to se=
parate out Tesla=E2=80=99s AI engineers from the =0Arest of the company and=
 house them in an AI-specific business, with its own =0Astock, to motivate =
them to build AI faster and for broader use cases than just =0ATesla.=0A=0A=
Other companies might have that thought and, like, spin out the AI company =
to =0Ashareholders, or build it as a private subsidiary with some employee =
ownership, =0Aorsomething where corporate formalities are observed and the =
public company=E2=80=99s =0Aexisting shareholders capture some of the value=
. Tesla is different!=0A=0A=0AFake tender=0A=0AWell, what does =E2=80=9Cfa=
ke=E2=80=9D mean, really=3F There are shades of gray. Ordinarily, =0Awhen a=
 buyer first announces an offer to acquire a public company, the buyer =0Ad=
oesn=E2=80=99t have enough money on hand to buy the target. This was true w=
henElon =0AMusk offered to buy Twitter Inc. =0A<https://www.bloomberg.com/o=
pinion/articles/2022-04-15/sure-elon-musk-might-buy-twitter=3Fcmpid=3DBBD09=
0924_MONEYSTUFF&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_source=3Dnewsletter&utm_term=3D24090=
9&utm_campaign=3Dmoneystuff>=0A, [7]  <> it is normally true when a big pri=
vate equity firm proposes a =0Aleveraged buyout, and it is sometimes true e=
ven when a big public company =0Aoffers to buy a smaller competitor for cas=
h. It is not uncommon to make a =0Apublic offer on the basis of =E2=80=9CI=
=E2=80=99m fairly confident someone would give us the =0Amoney,=E2=80=9D an=
d it=E2=80=99s pretty common to sign a merger agreement on the basis of =0A=
commitment letters from banks rather than actual cash.=0A=0ABut there are s=
ome potential buyers =E2=80=94 big public companies, big private equity =0A=
funds, Elon Musk I guess =E2=80=94 who, when they say =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m =
fairly confident someone =0Awould give us the money,=E2=80=9D areprobably c=
orrect, and there are others who are =0Areasonably mistaken, and then there=
 are others who are doing a bit. We talked =0Alast month =0A<https://www.bl=
oomberg.com/opinion/articles/2024-08-27/accounting-isn-t-cool-anymore=3Fcmp=
id=3DBBD090924_MONEYSTUFF&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_source=3Dnewsletter&utm_te=
rm=3D240909&utm_campaign=3Dmoneystuff>=0A about Edgar Bronfman=E2=80=99s fi=
zzled bid to buy Paramount Global, where the story =0Amight have been that =
Bronfman is a rich well-connected guy who really thought =0Ahe could raise =
the money and who had some serious financial partners, and =0AParamount eng=
aged with him because they also thought he could get the money, =0Abut ulti=
mately they decided they weren=E2=80=99t sure enough to keep talking to him=
.=0A=0ABut we also talked a few months ago =0A<https://www.bloomberg.com/o=
pinion/articles/2024-06-20/virgin-orbit-had-a-fake-takeover=3Fcmpid=3DBBD09=
0924_MONEYSTUFF&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_source=3Dnewsletter&utm_term=3D24090=
9&utm_campaign=3Dmoneystuff>=0A about Matthew Brown=E2=80=99s fizzled bid t=
o buy Virgin Orbit Holdings Inc., where the =0ASEC charged him with fraud b=
ecause at one point he allegedly =E2=80=9Csent Virgin Orbit =0Aa fabricated=
 screenshot of his company=E2=80=99s bank account, claiming it held $182 =
=0Amillion when in reality it had a balance of less than $1.=E2=80=9D This =
does not seem =0Alike a case of a guy who had serious financing partners an=
d a high likelihood =0Aof raising the money, but then it didn=E2=80=99t wor=
k out. This seems like a case of a =0Aguy who had $1 and thought it would b=
e fun to pretend to buy a public company.=0A=0AThat happens a lot, oddly. O=
ften, when people pretend to buy a public company, =0Ait is with the goal o=
f manipulating the stock: You buy some stock, you announce =0Aa fake takeov=
er, the stock goes up and you sell. But this is not at all =0Anecessary, an=
d a lot of people seem to just enjoy pretending to buy public =0Acompanies.=
 When we talked about Brown, I wrote:=0A=0AI am always open to the possibil=
ity that some people pretend to do takeovers =0Afor other reasons, not beca=
use they want to make a quick illegal profit on the =0Astock but because th=
ey want toget attention and feel important and conduct =0Ahigh-stakes negot=
iations. Fictional high-stakes negotiations, of course =E2=80=94 if =0Athey=
 agree on a price for the company, they=E2=80=99re not going topay it =E2=
=80=94 but, still, =0Afun role-playing.=0A=0AAnyway last year Esmark Inc. m=
ade a very weird public announcement of an offer =0Ato buy US Steel Corp. E=
smark is a private company run by a guy named James =0ABouchard, and it was=
 unclear if it had the capacity to buy US Steel. Also the =0Aoffer did not =
look like a real offer: It was styled a =E2=80=9Cvoluntary public cash =0Aa=
nd exchange offer,=E2=80=9D but there were no tender offer filings and the =
wording was =0Aodd. Also Bouchard went and told a reporter =E2=80=9Cwe have=
 the cash,=E2=80=9D which,I pointed =0Aout =0A<https://www.bloomberg.com/op=
inion/articles/2023-08-23/could-sculptor-be-better-or-cheaper=3Fcmpid=3DBBD=
