e SEC fined Esmark and Bouchard =0A<https://www.sec.gov/newsroom/press-rele=
ases/2024-117> a total of $600,000 for =0Adoing what I guess you=E2=80=99d =
call a fake tender offer. Fromthe order =0A<https://www.sec.gov/files/litig=
ation/admin/2024/34-100957.pdf>:=0A=0AOn August 15, 2023, Bouchard particip=
ated in an interview on CNBC regarding =0AEsmark=E2=80=99s press release. D=
uring the interview, he stated that Esmark has no debt =0Aand runs off cash=
. He further stated that Esmark has $10 billion in cash =0Acommitted to th=
e deal and would not put up any of Esmark=E2=80=99s assets as collateral.=
=0A=0AStatements in the press release and interview were false. Esmark and =
Bouchard =0Adid not have a reasonable belief that Esmark had the financial =
means to =0Acomplete the tender offer. As of August 31, 2023, Esmark had le=
ss than 1% of =0Athe required $7.8 billion in cash to complete the tender o=
ffer.=0A=0A=E2=80=9CLess than 1% of the required $7.8 billion=E2=80=9D coul=
d still be tens of millions of =0Adollars. There is no suggestion of market=
 manipulation here; the SEC=E2=80=99s only =0Apoint is that he didn=E2=80=
=99t have the money and went on television saying he did. I =0Asuppose maki=
ng a public offer to buy a famous public company is a way to get on =0Atele=
vision, and some people want that.=0A=0A=0AThings happen=0A=0AActivist push=
es for end of Murdoch voting control =0A<https://www.ft.com/content/253d144=
